<section>
  <h2>Presentation Guidelines</h2>

  <p>
    All participants are expected to present a <strong>one-slide lightning talk</strong> and an
    <strong>A3 poster</strong> on their research. These contributions must be submitted by
    <strong>11:59 PM Tuesday 17 March</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Virtual participants are also encouraged to submit a poster introducing their research.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h3>Lightning Talk</h3>

  <p><strong>The technical bits:</strong> three minutes, one slide, one minute for questions.</p>

  <h4>Three minutes?</h4>
  <p>
    Yes. Three minutes is intentionally not enough time to present in-depth results.
    It is just enough time to introduce yourself: who you are, what drives your work,
    and what conversations you would like to have during the event.
  </p>

  <p>
    The goal is to help others understand who you are as an atmospheric scientist.
    What are you curious about? What skills do you want to improve? What is something
    you would like to work on but have not yet had the chance to pursue?
  </p>

  <h4>What should I put on the slide?</h4>
  <p>
    Anything that best introduces you and your research interests to the community.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h3>A3 Poster</h3>

  <p>
    <strong>The technical bits:</strong> Posters must be <strong>A3 size</strong>
    (<strong>landscape preferred</strong>). Posters will be printed and displayed by the
    organisers. Simply submit your file by <strong>11:59 PM Tuesday</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    These mini-posters serve as a visual starting point for conversations about your
    research interests. Like the lightning talks, they are not intended to require
    extensive preparation or to function as a professional summary of your work.
  </p>

  <p>
    Instead, they provide an opportunity to introduce yourself and your research
    interests. Possible content includes:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>An intriguing result from the literature motivating one of your projects</li>
    <li>A method or dataset you use or created</li>
    <li>A key result from a past or current study</li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Recommendation:</strong> include three figures or fewer.</p>

  <p>Your poster should include:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Your name</li>
    <li>Your affiliation (institution and any relevant collaborators)</li>
    <li>A response to one or more prompts such as:</li>
  </ul>

  <blockquote>
    <p>“I wish I knew somebody else who wants to work on … ”</p>
    <p>“I think everyone is wrong about … ”</p>
    <p>“If I never had to think about funding again, I would research … ”</p>
    <p>“In my next job/project, I want to … ”</p>
    <p>“I’m thinking about a career pivot into … ”</p>
    <p>“In my spare time, I … ”</p>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    Posters may also be published, with your permission, on the group website to
    introduce your research and interests to community members who cannot attend
    in person.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you do <strong>not</strong> want your poster displayed online, indicate this in
    the <em>“Display on website”</em> field on the submission form.
  </p>
</section>
